<font color="#FF0000">REPLY TO CHRIS</font><br>
<tt>Wed Mar 12  6:17:05 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Chris,<br><br>
It seems that there are things that weigh heavily on your mind. Indeed, the Vietnam War sparked a political consciousness that has, and will persist, for many decades to come. I feel the Wall will keep that consciousness alive. It is not only a reminder of those who died and our connection with them, but it is a constant reminder to our government that the people really did not like what they saw and what happened. There were those in our government who opposed the Wall. I guess it lacked the neo-classical architectural tom-foolery so common to many monuments that are everywhere in Washington that try cause you to believe what they want and forget some of the reality behind the person or event. Like the Lincoln Memorial, which is really one of the few monuments that touch me deeply, the wall is a simple and honest statement that embodies all of our thoughts and our views.<br><br>
You said:<br><br>
&gt;&quot;...we'd throw all the corrupt and self-serving career     politicians the hell out of Washington, and we'd all work together to move beyond war towards a true and lasting peace.&quot;&lt;<br><br>
If everyone were to focus on the Wall and its meanings, it is the **one permanent protest** that will continue to work toward your view of politicians and peace. Is should not surprise you that I could not agree more.<br><br>
&gt;&quot;You were acting honorably out of your oath and your duty to your country.&quot;&lt;<br><br>
Thanks for your insight into this issue. It always amazes me how many people have a problem in understanding and accepting the amazingly simple concept of oath and duty. Sure, I had feelings about what was going on, but I made choices that were right for me and what at the time I saw was my place in the scheme of things. I continue to have no problem with that, regardless of how many protest the right or wrong of it. It was a decision that I made at the time with the mind of a 21 year old and a wellspring of personal conviction. Although I am different now, and age (hopefully wisdom) causes me to view things differently, I still feel that it was right for me. The *outcome* of that decision is a separate and distinct matter to be considered on wholly different grounds.<br><br>
&gt;&quot;What really frightens me is that it seems like all of this was being said in the '60s, but nothing has changed,...&quot;&lt;<br><br>
Chris, this frightens me too. My 50 year old wisdom is telling me that. This is an area I am really exploring deeply now. I had a remarkable and rare opportunity lately to interact with others of *many* different points of view. This feeling is among those that broke through universally.<br>
We are not alone.<br><br>
Arthur<br>
 
